            "id": "e360dc747c2a48ed9c3f5",
            "questionText": "An aerosol can contains a gas at an initial pressure of $!$200\\,\\mathrm{kPa}$!$ and an initial temperature of $!$27^{\\circ}\\mathrm{C}$!$. The can is left in direct sunlight, causing its temperature to rise to $!$57^{\\circ}\\mathrm{C}$!$. Assuming the volume of the can remains constant and the gas behaves ideally, calculate the new pressure inside the can.",
            "imageText": "",
            "steps": [
                {
                    "id": "ce443d5bced147e9b7f32",
                    "stepText": "Let's start by identifying the conversion relationship from Celsius to Kelvin. Which of the following formulas correctly converts a temperature in Celsius ($!$\\theta\\,^{\\circ}\\mathrm{C}$!$) to Kelvin ($!$T\\,\\mathrm{K}$!$)?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "f4186011-be31-4acd-ae74-62cc65bae364",
                        "cfa65469-32ab-41bb-ba28-7a4efd72bea1"
                    ],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$T = \\theta + 273$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$T = \\theta - 273$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$T = 273 - \\theta$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "d252219225024b9e85c95",
                    "stepText": "Now, using the conversion relationship, convert the initial temperature of $!$27^{\\circ}\\mathrm{C}$!$ to Kelvin. Perform the addition without revealing the result.",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        "300"
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "K",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "f4186011-be31-4acd-ae74-62cc65bae364"
                    ],
                    "options": []
                },
                {
                    "id": "f59962b8ec654d9f8ec57",
                    "stepText": "Next, convert the final temperature of $!$57^{\\circ}\\mathrm{C}$!$ to Kelvin using the same relationship. Calculate the sum to obtain the absolute temperature.",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        "330"
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "K",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "f4186011-be31-4acd-ae74-62cc65bae364"
                    ],
                    "options": []
                },
                {
                    "id": "66da39cb517f417aaeb3d",
                    "stepText": "Great, now that we have the absolute temperatures, which gas law relates pressure and temperature for a gas at constant volume? Choose the correct concept.",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "2adfd026-0718-4727-9c26-9492969f7ec0"
                    ],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$p \\propto T$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$p \\propto \\frac{1}{T}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$p \\propto V$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "1827f6d7de7e45fcb54a4",
                    "stepText": "Finally, use the relationship $!$\\frac{p_1}{T_1} = \\frac{p_2}{T_2}$!$ to calculate the new pressure. Multiply the initial pressure by the ratio of the final to the initial absolute temperature. Compute the value without disclosing the correct formula details.",
